I feel a certain kind of kinship to Shannon and @blindmelonband’s music. Like him, I grew up in a small midwest city playing in metal bands and listening to the Grateful Dead among other influences from my older siblings. To be clear, I’m in no way comparing myself to him…He’s one of a kind…There is no other, but I do feel a thread between us. If you’re from the Midwest you know what I mean. We have a way, an easy kind of being. Hell, we could make friends with the devil and sometimes we do. I didn’t know Shannon but I can only imagine he had this in him. I’m just grateful for his true artistry, freedom of spirit, and willingness to go out on that edge where most won’t go just to bring back something beautiful for the people.
It was an honor to sing this song with @goosetheband and pay tribute to one of the greats. 
In closing, I’ll leave you with this.
“I know we can’t all stay here forever
So I’m gonna write my words on the face of today and then they’ll paint it”
RIP Shannon.

I watched @scottweiland and the @stpband as a young artist and thought…that’s the energy I want to create on stage. Hello from The Diner in Fon du Lac, Wisconsin. This place has seen it all it seems. There’s just something about these old places, the smell, the wallpaper, the big red booths. They ignite a certain feeling of nostalgia in me that’s very comforting. My pops and I used to have breakfast at place like this in Hamilton back when I was a wee lad. It was called Andy’s. I don’t think it’s around anymore unfortunately but it did have a great run. Very fond memories of those times. I’d order a triple order of home fries with a mound of ketchup. Today my order is a lil different😉. Headed to Chicago for the big party that is @lollapalooza …wish me luck.

A little history:
The history of the building dates back to 1884 with an address of 577 Main St. (Prior to 1904, buildings were numbered starting at Lake Winnebago).
From 1884 to 1893 owner Ernest Heiden ran a saloon on the main floor, while Paul Vandervoort held his veterinary surgeon's office on the 2nd floor.
From 1893-1900 Peter Scholl operated a boot and shoe store at this location. Around this time, the original building was split in half, as there is also a listing for "The Diamond", a saloon owned by John Fitzgerald at 577 1/2 Main Street.
1915-1919 The building was converted into a restaurant.
1919-1926 At this time, the building was used as a vulcanizing shop under the name
"Wallicks and Hayward", and later "Hayward and Williams"
1930-1938 Converted back into a restaurant (owner John Voudiotis)
1940-1942 Restaurant operated by John V Richter
1942-1944 "Stavis Restaurant"
1944-1968 Douglas' Restaurant (owner John N. Douglas)
1969-1973 "Mannen's Restaurant"
1974 "E&R Restaurant"
1976-1982 "Koenen's Restaurant"
1983 "Jerry's Diner"
1984-2014 "Joan's Kitchen" (owner Joan Rait)
2014-2023 "Connie's Diner (owners Wally and Connie Shaffer
2023- current Sandy Ritchie takes over the diner as a lifelong Fond du Lac resident with 35 years of restaurant management.
The second story was made into boarding rooms with a hallway separating the two sides.
Later, electricity and plumbing were installed and the floor above the diner became a 3 bedroom apartment, however no one has lived there since 1960.

This old boy decided to jump into my lap this morning… I couldn’t resist the chance for a photo op..such a beautiful peaceful fella. Total purr boi…excited to get back home to my guy though. Tellurides a dream.

I’m so proud of this amazing person. You know her as Sam but I know her as lil boo, Jo, Sammy, booby, lil babe, baby bunz, hunny bunz, lil nug…the list goes on…it’s her birthday today so let’s celebrate and shower her with the love she so deserves. I’m honestly in awe of her and her way every. single. day. The amount of love and passion that she puts into her work and daily life is inspiring on a whole other level. Just by being with an around her, I’ve grown in ways that I never thought possible. If you know her you know what I’m talking about. You can feel the way she loves. Happy birthday Sam. Love you💜
